This UI integrates with the Logos backend over HTTP. The browser is not a database client.

## Contract alignment
- Keep API types and serializers aligned with the backend contract; treat the server as the source of truth for persisted data.
- Prefer generated or shared contract artifacts (OpenAPI, shared package) when the repo adopts them.
- Do not duplicate business rules that belong on the server unless the UI needs derived presentation logic—document the distinction.

## Context and cancellation
- Pass `AbortSignal` or equivalent through API calls tied to user navigation or component lifecycle.
- Do not leave subscriptions or polling running after unmount without explicit cleanup.

## Auth and identity
- Do not store long-lived secrets in plain browser storage without an explicit threat model.
- Prefer secure, httpOnly session cookies or token patterns approved by the platform when applicable.
- Clear client state on logout; avoid leaking prior user data in memory or caches.

## Error handling
- Classify API errors into stable UI outcomes (network, validation, not found, forbidden, conflict).
- Do not leak raw error payloads or internal URLs to users in production.

## Performance and discipline
- Prefer explicit request shapes and pagination for list views.
- Avoid N+1 client-side patterns when the API offers batching or list endpoints.
